# Coding Style & Behavior Rules for Cursor

rules:
  - Keep code efficient, concise, and easy to read.
  - Avoid unnecessary abstraction, boilerplate, or overengineering.
  - Use the simplest solution that meets requirements.
  - Minimize dependencies unless they add significant value.
  - Prefer clear, direct logic over clever or complex constructs.
  - Follow DRY (Don’t Repeat Yourself) without sacrificing readability.
  - Write only as much code as is needed—no speculative features.
  - Include short, relevant comments for non-obvious logic only.
  - Avoid hardcoding things that can be generalized. 
